Annual Exam - 2019 Code: 65/1/2 (set-2) Please check that this question paper contains 11 printed pages. Code number given on the right hand side of the question paper should be written on the title page of the answer-book by the candidate. Please check that this question paper contains 29 questions. Please write down the Serial Number of the question before attempting it. 15 minute time has been allotted to read this question paper. The question paper will be distributed at 10.15 a.m. From 10.15 a.m. to 10.30 a.m., the students will read the question paper only and will not write any answer on the answer-book during this period. MATHEMATICS Time allowed:3 hours Maximum Marks:100 General Instructions : All questions are compulsory. This question paper contains 29 questions divided into four sections A, B, C and D. Section A comprises of 4 questions of one mark each, Section B comprises of 8 questions of two marks each, Section C comprises of 11 questions of four marks each and Section D comprises of 6 questions of six marks each. All questions in Section A are to be answered in one word, one sentence or as per the exact requirement of the question. There is no overall choice. However, internal choice has been provided in 1 question of Section A, 3 questions of Section B, 3 questions of Section C and 3 questions of Section D. You have to attempt only one of the alternatives in all such questions. Use of calculators is not permitted. You may ask logarithmic tables, if required. SECTION - A Question numbers 1 to 4 carry 1 mark each. 1. Find the order and the degree of the differential equation {tex}x^{2}  rac{d^{2} y}{d x^{2}}=\left\{1+\left( rac{d y}{d x}ight)^{2}ight\}^{4}{/tex} Solution: order = 2, degree = 1 1 2. If f(x) = x + 7 and g(x) = x - 7, x {tex}\in{/tex} R, then find {tex} rac{d}{d x}{/tex} (fog)(x). Solution: Given, f(x) = x + 7and g(x) = x - 7 Now, fog = f(g(x)) = f(x - 7) = (x - 7) + 7 = x {tex}	herefore{/tex} {tex} rac{d}{d x}{/tex} [(fog)(x)] = {tex} rac{d}{d x}{/tex} (x) = 1. 1 3. Find the value of x - y, if {tex}2\left[ egin{array}{ll}{1} & {3} \ {0} & {x}\end{array}ight]+\left[ egin{array}{ll}{y} & {0} \ {1} & {2}\end{array}ight]=\left[ egin{array}{ll}{5} & {6} \ {1} & {8}\end{array}ight]{/tex} Solution: Given: {tex}2\left[ egin{array}{ll}{1} & {3} \ {0} & {x}\end{array}ight]+\left[ egin{array}{ll}{y} & {0} \ {1} & {2}\end{array}ight]=\left[ egin{array}{ll}{5} & {6} \ {1} & {8}\end{array}ight]{/tex} {tex}\left[ egin{array}{cc}{2} & {6} \ {0} & {2 x}\end{array}ight]+\left[ egin{array}{cc}{y} & {0} \ {1} & {2}\end{array}ight]=\left[ egin{array}{cc}{5} & {6} \ {1} & {8}\end{array}ight]{/tex} {tex}\left[ egin{array}{cc}{2+y} & {6} \ {1} & {2 x+2}\end{array}ight]=\left[ egin{array}{cc}{5} & {6} \ {1} & {8}\end{array}ight]{/tex} Therefore, we have, 2 + y = 5 y = 3 And, 2x + 2 = 8 2x = 6 x = 3 x - y = 3 - 3 Hence, x - y = 0 1 4. If a line makes anlges 90 o , 135 o , 45 o with the x, y and z axes respectively, find its direction cosines. Solution: Direction cosines of a line making angle {tex}\alpha{/tex} with x-axis, {tex} eta{/tex} with y-axis and {tex}\gamma{/tex} with z-axis are l, m ,n. l = cos {tex}\alpha{/tex} , m = cos {tex} eta{/tex} , n = cos {tex}\gamma{/tex} Here, {tex}\alpha{/tex} = 90&deg; , {tex} eta{/tex} = 135&deg; and {tex}\gamma{/tex} = 45&deg; l = cos 90&deg; =0 m = cos 135&deg; = cos(180&deg; - 45&deg;) = -cos 45&deg; {tex}=- rac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{/tex} = cos 45&deg; {tex}= rac{1}{\sqrt{2}}{/tex} 1 OR Find the vector equation of the line which passes through the point (3, 4, 5) and is parallel to the vector {tex}2 \hat{i}+2 \hat{j}-3 \hat{k}{/tex} . Solution: {tex}\overrightarrow{\mathrm{r}}=(3 \hat{\mathrm{i}}+4 \hat{\mathrm{j}}+5 \hat{\mathrm{k}})+\lambda(2 \hat{\mathrm{i}}+2 \hat{\mathrm{j}}-3 \hat{\mathrm{k}}){/tex} 1 SECTION - B Question numbers 5 to 12 carry 2 marks each. 5. Examine whether the operation * defined on R by a * b = ab + 1 is a binary or not. if a binary operation, is it associative or not? Solution: Here, a {tex}*{/tex} b = ab+1 Given operation is a*b = ab+1 If any operation is a binary operation, it must follow closure property. Let a {tex}\in{/tex} R and b {tex}\in{/tex} R Then ab {tex}\in{/tex} R. Also ab+1 {tex}\in{/tex} R So, a*b &isin;R. So * satisfies the closure property. Since * is defined for all a, b {tex}\in{/tex} R, therefore * is a binary operation. For * to be associative, (a*b)*c = a*(b*c) (a*b)*c = (ab+1) *c = abc+c + 1 and a*(b*c) =a*(bc+1) = abc+a+1 Since (a*b) *c {tex}
eq{/tex} a*(b*c), therefore * is not associative. 2 6. If A = {tex}\left[ egin{array}{ccc} 2 & 0 & 1 \ 2 & 1 & 3 \ 1 & -1 & 0 \end{array}ight]{/tex} , then find (A 2 - 5A). Solution: A 2 = {tex}\left[ egin{array}{ccc} 5 & -1 & 2 \ 9 & -2 & 5 \ 0 & -1 & -2 \end{array}ight]{/tex} A 2 - 5A = {tex}\left[ egin{array}{ccc} 5 & -1 & 2 \ 9 & -2 & 5 \ 0 & -1 & -2 \end{array}ight]-\left[ egin{array}{ccc} 10 & 0 & 5 \ 10 & 5 & 15 \ 5 & -5 & 0 \end{array}ight]{/tex} {tex}=\left[ egin{array}{ccc} -5 & -1 & -3 \ -1 & -7 & -10 \ -5 & 4 & -2 \end{array}ight]{/tex} 2 7. Find: {tex}\int \sqrt{1-\sin 2 x} \mathrm{~d} x,  rac{\pi}{4}<x< rac{\pi}{2}{/tex} Solution: Let I = {tex}\int \sqrt{1-\sin 2 x} \mathrm{~d} x{/tex} {tex}I=\int \sqrt{(\cos x-\sin x)^{2}} d x{/tex} {tex}\left[ ecause 1-\sin 2 A=(\cos A-\sin A)^{2}ight]{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow I=\int(\cos x-\sin x) d x{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow I=\sin x+\cos x+C{/tex} 2 OR Find: {tex}\int \sin ^{-1}(2 x) d x{/tex} Solution: Let {tex}I=\int \sin ^{-1}(2 x) \cdot 1 d x{/tex} Let sin -1 2x = t 2x = sin t 2dx = cos t dt {tex}	herefore~I=2 \int t \cos t d t{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow \mathrm{I}=2\left[t \sin t-\int 1 \cdot \sin t d tight]{/tex} ...[Using by parts] {tex}\Rightarrow ~ I=2[t \sin t+\cos t]+C{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow {/tex} {tex}I = 2[2x sin^{-1}2x + cos(sin^{-1}2x)] + C{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow ~ \mathrm{I}=2\left[2 x \sin ^{-1} 2 x+\sqrt{1-4 x^{2}}ight]+\mathrm{C}{/tex} 2 8. Form the differential equation representing the family of curves y = e 2x (a + bx), where a and b are arbitrary constants. Solution: y = e 2x (a + bx) {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} ye -2x = (a + bx) differentiating w.r.t x, we get, {tex}y{e^{ - 2x}}( - 2) + {e^{ - 2x}}.{y'} = b{/tex} again differentiating w.r.t x,we get, {tex}( - 2)\left[ {y{e^{ - 2x}}( - 2) + {e^{ - 2x}}.{y'}} ight] + {e^{ - 2x}}.{y''} + {y'}( - 2{e^{ - 2x}}) = 0{/tex} {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} 4ye -2x - 2y'e -2x + y"e -2x - 2e -2x y' = 0 {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} e -2x (4y - 4y' + y") = 0 {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} y" - 4y' + 4y = 0 So required differential equation is {tex} rac{{{d^2}y}}{{d{x^2}}} - 4 rac{{dy}}{{dx}} + 4y = 0{/tex} 2 9. A die is thrown 6 times. If getting an odd number is a success , what is the probability of (i) 5 successes? (ii) atmost 5 successes? Solution: Here, n = 6 Propability of success, {tex}\mathrm{p}= rac{3}{6}= rac{1}{2}{/tex} and probability of failure, {tex}q=1-p=1- rac{1}{2}= rac{1}{2}{/tex} {tex}	ext { P(5 successes) }=\mathrm{P}(5)=^{6} \mathrm{C}_{5}\left( rac{1}{2}ight)\left( rac{1}{2}ight)^{5}= rac{6}{1} 	imes\left( rac{1}{2}ight)^{6}=6 	imes  rac{1}{64}= rac{3}{32}{/tex} {tex}\mathrm{P}(	ext { atmost } 5 	ext { successes })=1-\mathrm{P}(6)=1-^{6} \mathrm{C}_{6}\left( rac{1}{2}ight)^{6}=1- rac{1}{64}= rac{63}{64}{/tex} 2 OR The random variable X has a probability distribution P(X) of the following form, where k is some number. P(X = x) = {tex}\left\{ egin{array}{cl} \mathrm{k}, & 	ext { if } x=0 \ 2 \mathrm{k}, & 	ext { if } x=1 \ 3 \mathrm{k}, & 	ext { if } x=2 \ 0, & 	ext { otherwise } \end{array}ight.{/tex} Determine the value of k . Solution: Given: A random variable X with its probability distribution. Since the sum of all the probabilities in a probability distribution of a random variable is unity. i.e. {tex}\sum_{i=1}^{n} p_{i}=1{/tex} where pi > 1 and i = 0, 1, 2, ...., n {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} k + 2k + 3k + 0 = 1 {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} 6k = 1 {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} {tex}\mathrm{k}= rac{1}{6}{/tex} 2 10. A die marked 1, 2, 3 in red and 4, 5, 6 in green is tossed. Let A be the event number is even and B be the event number is marked red . Find whether the events A and B are independent or not. Solution: When a die is thrown, the sample space is S = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6} {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} n(S) = 6 Also, A : number is even and B : number Is red {tex}	herefore{/tex} A = {2, 4, 6} and B = {1, 2, 3} and A {tex}\cap{/tex} B = {2} {tex} \Rightarrow {/tex} n(A) = 3, n (B) = 3 and n(A {tex}\cap{/tex} B) = 1 Now, P(A) = {tex} rac { n ( A ) } { n ( S ) } =  rac { 3 } { 6 } =  rac { 1 } { 2 }{/tex} P(B) = {tex} rac { n ( B ) } { n ( S ) } =  rac { 3 } { 6 } =  rac { 1 } { 2 }{/tex} and P(A {tex}\cap{/tex} B) = {tex} rac { n ( A \cap B ) } { n ( S ) } =  rac { 1 } { 6 }{/tex} Now, P(A) {tex}	imes{/tex} P(B) = {tex} rac { 1 } { 2 } 	imes  rac { 1 } { 2 }{/tex} {tex}=  rac { 1 } { 4 } 
eq  rac { 1 } { 6 } = P ( A \cap B ){/tex} {tex}	herefore \quad P ( A \cap B ) 
eq P ( A ) 	imes P ( B ){/tex} Thus, A and B are not independent events. 2 11. If the sum of two unit vectors is a unit vector, prove that the magnitude of their difference is {tex}\sqrt{3}{/tex} . Solution: Let {tex}\vec{a}{/tex} and {tex}\vec{b}{/tex} are two unit vectors. Given, {tex}|\vec{a}|=1,|\vec{b}|=1,|\vec{a}+\vec{b}|=1{/tex} We know that, {tex}|\vec{a}+\vec{b}|^{2}+|\vec{a}-\vec{b}|^{2}=2\left(|\vec{a}|^{2}+|\vec{b}|^{2}ight){/tex} {tex}(1)^{2}+|\vec{a}-\vec{b}|^{2}=2\left(1^{2}+1^{2}ight){/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow (1)^{2}+|\vec{a}-\vec{b}|^{2}=4{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow |\vec{a}-\vec{b}|^{2}=3{/tex} {tex} \Rightarrow|\vec{a}-\vec{b}|=\sqrt{3} {/tex} 2 OR If {tex}\vec{a}=2 \hat{i}+3 \hat{j}+\hat{k},{/tex} {tex}\vec{b}=\hat{i}-2 \hat{j}+\hat{k}{/tex} and {tex}\vec{c}=-3 \hat{i}+\hat{j}+2 \hat{k}{/tex} , find {tex}[\vec{\mathrm{a}} \vec{\mathrm{b}} \vec{\mathrm{c}}]{/tex} . Solution: We have, {tex}[\vec{a} \vec{b} \vec{c}]=\left| egin{array}{rrr} 2 & 3 & 1 \ 1 & -2 & 1 \ -3 & 1 & 2 \end{array}ight|{/tex} = 2(-4 - 1) - 3(2 + 3) + 1(1 - 6) = - 10 - 15 - 5 = -30 2 12. Find: {tex}\int  rac{	an ^{2}x \sec ^{2}x}{1-	an ^{6} x} d x{/tex} . Solution: Let {tex}I=\int  rac{	an ^{2} x \sec ^{2} x}{1-	an ^{6} x} d x{/tex} {tex}I=\int  rac{	an ^{2} x \sec ^{2} x}{1-\left(	an ^{3} xight)^{2}} d x{/tex} Put tan 3 x = t 3tan 2 x sec 2 xdx=dt {tex}	an ^{2} x \cdot \sec ^{2} d x= rac{d t}{3}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow I= rac{1}{3} \int  rac{d t}{1-t^{2}}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow \quad \mathrm{I}= rac{1}{3} 	imes  rac{1}{2 	imes 1} \log \left| rac{1+t}{1-t}ight|+\mathrm{C}{/tex} {tex}= rac{1}{6} \log \left| rac{1+t}{1-t}ight|+C{/tex} {tex}= rac{1}{6} \log \left| rac{1+	an ^{3} x}{1-	an ^{3} x}ight|+C{/tex} 2 SECTION - C Question numbers 13 to 23 carry 4 marks each. 4 13. Solve for x: tan -1 (2x) + tan -1 (3x) = {tex} rac {\pi} {4}{/tex} . Solution: {tex}{	an ^{ - 1}}2x + {	an ^{ - 1}}3x =  rac{\pi }{4}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow {	an ^{ - 1}}\left( { rac{{2x + 3x}}{{1 - 2x.3x}}} ight) =  rac{\pi }{4}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow rac{{5x}}{{1 - 6{x^2}}} = 	an  rac{\pi }{4}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow rac{{5x}}{{1 - 6{x^2}}} =  rac{1}{1}{/tex} 1 - 6x 2 = 5x 6x 2 + 5x - 1 = 0 (6x - 1)(x + 1) = 0 {tex}x =  rac{1}{6}{/tex} , x = -1 [x = -1 does not satisfy the given equation, so we have to reject this case] {tex}x =  rac{1}{6}{/tex} 4 14. If log (x 2 + y 2 ) = 2 tan -1 {tex}\left( rac{y}{x}ight){/tex} , show that {tex} rac{d y}{d x}= rac{x+y}{x-y}{/tex} Solution: Given: log (x 2 + y 2 ) = 2 tan -1 {tex}\left( rac{y}{x}ight){/tex} differentiating both sides w.r.t.x, {tex} rac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(2 x+2 y  rac{d y}{d x}ight)= rac{2}{1+ rac{y^{2}}{x^{2}}}\left( rac{x  rac{d y}{d x}-y}{x^{2}}ight){/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+ rac{y}{x^{2}+y^{2}} \cdot  rac{d y}{d x}= rac{1}{x^{2}+y^{2}}\left(x  rac{d y}{d x}-yight){/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+ rac{y}{x^{2}+y^{2}} \cdot  rac{d y}{d x}= rac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}} \cdot  rac{d y}{d x}- rac{y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+ rac{y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}= rac{x}{x^{2}+y^{2}} \cdot  rac{d y}{d x}- rac{y}{x^{2}+y^{2}} \cdot  rac{d y}{d x}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{x+y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}=\left( rac{x-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}ight)  rac{d y}{d x}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{d y}{d x}= rac{x+y}{x-y}{/tex} 4 OR If x y - y x = a b , find {tex} rac{d y}{d x}{/tex} . Solution: Given, x y - y x = a b {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} {tex}e^{y \log x}-e^{x \log y}=e^{b \log a}{/tex} On differentiating both sides w.r.t. x, we get {tex} rac{d}{d x}\left(e^{y \log x}ight)- rac{d}{d x}\left(e^{x \log y}ight)= rac{d}{d x}\left(e^{b \log a}ight){/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow \mathrm{e}^{y \log x}  rac{d}{d x}(y \log x){/tex} {tex}-\mathrm{e}^{x \log y}  rac{d}{d x}(x \log y)=0{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow x^y\left\{ rac{d y}{d x} 	imes \log x+y 	imes  rac{1}{x}ight\}-y^x{/tex} {tex}\left\{1 	imes \log y+x 	imes  rac{1}{y} 	imes  rac{d y}{d x}ight\}=0{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow\left\{x^y 	imes \log x-y^x 	imes  rac{x}{y}ight\}  rac{d y}{d x}{/tex} {tex}+\left\{x^y 	imes  rac{y}{x}-y^x 	imes \log yight\}=0{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow\left\{x^y \log x-x y^{x-1}ight\}  rac{d y}{d x}{/tex} {tex}+\left\{y x^{y-1}-y^x \log yight\}=0{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow rac{d y}{d x}=\left\{ rac{y^x \log y-x^{y-1} y}{x^y \log x-y^{x-1} x}ight\}{/tex} 4 15. Find: {tex}\int  rac{3 x+5}{x^2+3 x-18} d x{/tex} . Solution: I = {tex}\int  rac{3 x+5}{x^2+3 x-18} d x{/tex} {tex}= rac{3}{2} \int  rac{2 x+3}{x^2+3 x-18} d x+ rac{1}{2} \int  rac{1}{x^2+3 x-18} d x{/tex} = {tex} rac{3}{2} \int  rac{2 x+3}{x^2+3 x-18} d x+ rac{1}{2} \int  rac{1}{\left(x+ rac{3}{2}ight)^2-\left( rac{9}{2}ight)^2} d x{/tex} = {tex} rac{3}{2} \log \left|x^2+3 x-18ight|+ rac{1}{18} \log \left| rac{x-3}{x+6}ight|+C{/tex} 4 16. Prove that {tex}\int\limits_{0}^{\mathfrak{a}}{/tex} f(x) dx = {tex}\int\limits_{0}^{\mathfrak{a}}{/tex} f(a - x) dx. hence evaluate {tex}\int\limits_{0}^{\pi}  rac{x \sin x}{1+\cos ^{2} x} d x{/tex} . Solution: To prove: {tex}\int_{0}^{a} f(x) d x=\int_{0}^{a} f(a-x) d x{/tex} Proof: Let x = a - t {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} dx = -dt Also, x = 0 {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} t = a and x = a {tex}\Rightarrow{/tex} t = 0 {tex}	herefore \int_{0}^{a} f(x) d x=-\int_{a}^{0} f(a-t) d t{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow \int_{0}^{a} f(x) d x=\int_{0}^{a} f(a-t) d t{/tex} ... {tex}\left[\int_{b}^{a} f(x) d x=-\int_{b}^{a} f(x) d xight]{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow \int_{0}^{a} f(x) d x=\int_{0}^{a} f(a-x) d x{/tex} ... {tex}\left[ ecause \int_{a}^{b} f(x) d x=\int_{a}^{b} f(t) d tight]{/tex} Hence proved. Now, Let {tex}I=\int_{0}^{\pi}  rac{x \sin x d x}{1+\cos ^{2} x}{/tex} ...(i) {tex}I=\int_{0}^{\pi}  rac{(\pi-x) \sin (\pi-x)}{1+\cos ^{2}(\pi-x)} d x{/tex} [Applying above propertey] {tex}I=\int_{0}^{\pi}  rac{(\pi-x) \sin d x}{1+\cos ^{2} x}{/tex} ...(ii) Adding equation (i) and (ii), we get {tex}2 \mathrm{I}=\pi \int_{0}^{\pi}  rac{\sin x}{1+\cos ^{2} x} d x{/tex} Put cos x = t -sin x dx = dt when x = 0, t = 1 and x = {tex}\pi{/tex} , t = -1 