 \Rightarrow 	heta=\pi {/tex} {tex} \Rightarrow \overrightarrow{A B} 	ext { and } \overrightarrow{C D} {/tex} and unlike parallel vectors. Hence, lines AB and CD are parallel. 4 18. Using properties of determinants, prove the following: {tex}\left| egin{array}{ccc}{a+b+c} & {-c} & {-b} \ {-c} & {a+b+c} & {-a} \ {-b} & {-a} & {a+b+c}\end{array}ight|{/tex} = 2(a + b) (b + c) (c + a). Solution: {tex}\operatorname{LHS}=\left| egin{array}{ccc}{a+b+c} & {-c} & {-b} \ {-c} & {a+b+c} & {-a} \ {-b} & {-a} & {a+b+c}\end{array}ight|{/tex} Applying R 2 {tex}ightarrow{/tex} R 2 + R 1 and R 3 {tex}ightarrow{/tex} R 3 + R 1 we get {tex}=\left| egin{array}{ccc}{a+b+c} & {-c} & {-b} \ {a+b} & {a+b} & {-(a+b)} \ {a+c} & {-(a+c)} & {a+c}\end{array}ight|{/tex} Taking (a+b) common from R 2 and (a+c) common from R 3 , we get {tex}=(a+b)(a+c)\left| egin{array}{ccc}{a+b+c} & {-c} & {-b} \ {1} & {1} & {-1} \ {1} & {-1} & {1}\end{array}ight|{/tex} Now, Applying C 1 {tex} ightarrow{/tex} C 1 + C 2 , we get {tex}=(a+b)(a+c)\left| egin{array}{ccc}{(a+b)} & {-c} & {-b |} \ {2} & {1} & {-1} \ {0} & {-1} & {1}\end{array}ight|{/tex} Now, Expanding along R 3 , we get = (a + b)(a + c)[2(b+c)] = 2(a + b)(b + c)(c + a) = R.H.S. 4 19. If x = cos t + log tan {tex}( rac {t} {2}){/tex} , y = sin t, then find the values of {tex} rac{\mathrm{d}^2 \mathrm{y}}{\mathrm{dt}^2}{/tex} and {tex} rac{\mathrm{d}^2 \mathrm{y}}{\mathrm{dx}^2}{/tex} at t = {tex} rac {\pi} {4}{/tex} . Solution: Given that, x = cos t + log tan {tex} rac{t}{2}{/tex} , y = sin t Differentiating with respect to t, we have, {tex} rac{d x}{d t}=-\sin t+ rac{1}{	an  rac{t}{2}} 	imes \sec ^{2}  rac{t}{2} 	imes  rac{1}{2}{/tex} {tex}=-\sin t+ rac{1}{ rac{\sin  rac{t}{2}}{\cos  rac{t}{2}}} 	imes  rac{1}{\cos ^{2}  rac{t}{2}} 	imes  rac{1}{2}{/tex} {tex}=-\sin t+ rac{1}{2 \sin  rac{t}{2} \cos  rac{t}{2}}{/tex} {tex}=-\sin t+ rac{1}{\sin t}{/tex} {tex}= rac{1-\sin ^{2} t}{\sin t}{/tex} {tex}= rac{\cos ^{2} t}{\sin t}{/tex} = cos t {tex}	imes